U.S.: Repetition is the Mother of Wisdom
It is comical that Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the smartest man, as a diligent student repeats in the Afghan question the strategy of his predecessor, which he himself took for the dumbest.
When he finally revealed his eagerly awaited Afghan approach, it turned out to be a copy of the script used for Iraq by Bush, created three years ago.
Not only is the same text used several times the phrase "the same as in Iraq", but he also did not hesitate to use the title of Bush's January 2007 statement for his own statement: "A new way forward".
It was he himself, who three years ago criticized Bush’s idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country that is suffering from the civil war, and that criticized him as “an irresponsible decision with catastrophic consequences.”
The following months, however, showed that Bush’s strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only possible and successful one, so that today there is no talk of Iraq in the news.
Bush’s reputation did not improve, however objectively left his successor in a much more favorable initial situation than could be expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will be repeated.
The field captains again asked him to increase the military contingent, especially the commander-in-chief of Afghanistan's Operation General Stanley McCristal, who, despite traditional subordinate relations, subjected the undecided riflemen in the White House to harsh criticism.
He asked 40,000 men to improve the situation.
The president hesitated for three months, but he didn’t think of anything better, so at least he tricked the general over 10,000 military personnel.
He managed to get Europe to promise him another 5,000, although he himself previously had at least 10,000.
The most problematic thing about Obama’s entire strategy seems to be his goal, to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and to finish this procedure in three years.
Many doubt that the increase will bear the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars in recent years, Iraq’s society is relatively well organized, its leaders respect the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: no one can be trusted and no agreement is reached.
Under these conditions it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, if they are used to changing the chief every day according to their needs.
The political institutions, although formally established, will remain only a people of Potemkin, and patriarchal tribal relations will remain after him.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated because of confusing relations, even more complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Not even establishing a state that is “capable of action,” a minimum goal of the entire operation, seems very real.
The horizon of Obama’s strategy is shocked by his voluntarism.
For the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to worsen and is now about to erupt.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing of reality, can believe that the military sent to war to "go home soon", will do some miracle here.
From a political point of view, setting the date for the withdrawal of troops is pure irresponsibility, as the Taliban will consider it as an indirect declaration of U.S. defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that Europeans have less and less willingness to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians do not know, nor do they want to explain to their voters, what the security of Germany or Italy has to do with the war with the Hindu Kush.
The other factor, capable of radically affecting the situation, is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to worsen and the increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the US will have to make a difficult decision: try to solve the problem with military force or not.
It will be necessary to look for answers precisely when, according to Obama, America begins the triumphant withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, each such solution will mean a dramatic setback for the Afghan situation.
The only positive point for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years left before the presidential election and that is why there is still a long time to find another strategy, if it turns out to be a total failure.
