The pneumococcal vaccine will be free and voluntary
The pneumococcal vaccine from January will put an end to the usual habits.
As a first vaccine it should be free for families and at the same time voluntary.
However, there are already opinions that the mandatory vaccine would be more effective.
Preparations for the introduction of the free pneumococcal vaccine culminate.
The Institute of Medicines is already setting maximum prices for vaccines, which will be covered by insurance companies.
Experts have also already made it clear in the vaccination procedure.
The new vaccine
Free vaccines for children born in August
From January onwards, pneumococcal vaccine will be available free of charge to children born since August 2 last year.
The condition is that you have not received a dose of the vaccine before.
Those who started the vaccine last year or earlier have to cover other doses of the vaccine as well.
The first dose of the vaccine must be received between the third and fifth month of age of the child.
Last year, a quarter of families volunteered to vaccinate their children against pneumococcus.
Parents, however, paid for a dose of 1600 crowns and more.
To vaccinate younger children, four doses are needed.
Experts generally estimate, that insurance companies will spend 300 to 450 thousand crowns on vaccines annually.
Uncoupled will save on treatment, which is needed for unvaccinated children.
So far, the state has spent about 500,000 annually on all of the children’s vaccinations.
Covered vaccination was initiated by the so-called Janota package.
Pneumococcus is the cause of otitis media, but also of serious infections including meningitis and septicemia.
Pneumococcal infections in our country kill 28 children under the age of 10 every year, according to research in hospitals.
In addition to the Czech Republic, pneumococcal vaccine cover in children was introduced in approximately 40 countries.
Will the vaccine be mandatory?
However, at the same time there are opinions, that this vaccine could be mandatory in the future.
As of January, it must be covered by insurance and voluntary companies.
Compulsory vaccination would be better, said Rudolf Kalovsk<0xC3><0xBD>, the head of the Nahlas civic association.
Their association has been spreading pneumococcal vaccines for a long time.
The experts at an international conference, in which our association participated, were not completely satisfied with the fact that we have the voluntary vaccine.
It's not entirely ideal.
On the other hand, we are happy to achieve at least this.
I think this is the path we now have to take, Kalovsk<0xC3><0xBD> said.
The Ministry of Health, however, does not want to change the pneumococcal vaccination procedure.
At the moment we do not think at all, said his spokesman Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88>.
Voluntary vaccination has its drawbacks, doctors say
The president of the Society of Pediatricians Professional Society of Practical Child Physicians Hana Cabrnochov<0xC3><0xA1> recognizes, that the voluntary vaccine has its disadvantages.
"In the situation, when the vaccine costs such a high amount, we relatively understand the political decision to have started the vaccination as a volunteer," says Cabrnochov<0xC3><0xA1>.
Experts expect that by next year more than 80 percent of young parents will have their babies vaccinated against pneumococcus.
The pneumococcal vaccine is a big change too because as the first vaccination in children is covered by health companies, not by the state.
Insurance companies should spend more money on prophylaxis, to save on treatment, Cabrnochov<0xC3><0xA1> explains.
Doctors will have to buy the vaccines themselves.
However, pediatricians are concerned about the purchase of vaccines.
Previously, vaccines had to be bought by insurance companies and distributed to doctors, just like when the state gives them other vaccines.
Some MPs, however, were afraid that insurance companies could “take the money out of health insurance.”
Doctors will have to buy the vaccines and wait until they are paid by the insurance companies.
It is estimated, that pediatricians will invest in vaccines 40,000 a month, which is a remarkable sum.
It will not be easy, says Cabrnochova.
