Management revolution or end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain.
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies with regard to their employees recalls the position of companies with regard to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of collaborators adhering to "values" determined from above as before it was about imposing on consumers products designed by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave way to the strategies of conquering markets... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are not related to the preferences of customers is regularly repeated.
A demobilization of employees can end in a deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially of R&D and, even more, of business intelligence.
Indeed, BI (Business Intelligence) “requires all parties involved ... to have proactive behavior and forward-looking vision”; this needs commitment on the part of employees that is completely contrary to the recommendations of an authoritarian leadership.
For this reason, we call for a managerial revolution, which would consist of putting employees at the center of the concerns of the company as well as the client.
Internal opinion polls have a relative usefulness
Will internal opinion polls, such as the survey conducted by Orange among its employees, incite a managerial revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I was able to verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many laps, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did!
Second, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
-Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the great schools of engineers, they interpret psychology in a mechanistic way.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory that the American “neurosciences” recently reactivated, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media widely disseminated behind their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to manage executive engagement “commands”, a recent research by Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms executives in a mechanistic management posture, unsuited to today’s world.
Identifying and Measuring Mobilization Factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies, involves adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists of integrating into any business management reasoning or practice, a fundamental fact: for employees, engagement with the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means to make a part of their dreams, ambitions and projects come true.
Today, only studies from the Motifunctional Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
The studies showed that they judge their company based on a predetermined dox that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of mobilization factors, business executives can monitor, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and relocate human resource management "on the spot".
In this way, they create a favorable ground for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
