In a waking state, some people see images and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
Not only in the case of the mentally ill and drug addicts, the boundaries between imagination and reality are blurred.
As long as it happens during sleep, everything is in order.
When we are lying in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we can give ourselves without hindrance to the wildest imaginations and creations of fantasy.
However, anyone who experiences sleep-like states during waking, or sees and hears things that others do not see or hear, is most often considered in the modern Western world to be crazy or drug addict, or at least manic.
But such images and voices do not only arise in the mentally ill or in the drugged.
The fault lies with our imagination: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint pictures or write novels sometimes blur the boundaries between sleep, madness and reality.
Alert altered states of consciousness can appear in the most diverse forms, at best we call them visions, and at worst, madness.
Although the triggers and effects can be distinguished, the views of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the psychedelic experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Casta<0xC3><0xB1>eda, the states of shamanic possession, and psychosis and hallucinations can be referred to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of neuronal communication substances in the brain – especially dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and acetylcholine – has been derailed and the interaction between various parts of the brain is disturbed.
During a schizophrenic psychosis, very often complex hallucinations and crazy thoughts appear.
Gravity no longer has power over him.
The relationship between madness and sleep has occupied philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle conceived of hallucinations as a form of sleep in a waking state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, noted in 1861 a "great similarity of the state of madness with dream states", for Sigmund Freud, the dream was even "a psychosis, with all the misuses, formations and élocades".
It is the autumn of 2001, when Henning T. becomes a comic book character.
His body is two-dimensional and outrageously colorful.
Gravity no longer has power over it, it is floating near the ceiling of the room.
He feels a kick.
Behind him, figures of demons with wings, with red slits like blood, deformed, sharking teeth.
They are chasing him, kicking him with heavy, flaming boots, throwing him against the walls, he feels the pain all over his body.
Screaming and malignant voices resonate from the walls and the radio.
He can no longer stand them, the voices that insult and offend him.
Henning T. pulls two wires from the stereo, ties them to form a hanging knot, and fixes them on a hook on the ceiling.
He climbs on a horn and puts the knot around his neck.
Jump. Jump.
The rope loosens.
What a lesson for you!, shout the voices in a chorus that reverberates the eardrums, "Go to the clinic and have them heal you!"
Now, Henning T. is 40 years old and has experienced six acute psychoses, the last two years ago, the first almost 20 years ago.
The cause of this was LSD.
His diagnosis is schizo-affective-paranoid psychosis, he is also manic-depressive, taking medications, against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, for three years he has been married.
In psychosis I have experienced the most terrible anguish and the deepest despair, he says.
Hallucinations are a cruel reality
Approximately one percent of the population falls ill at least once in their lifetime of schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In acute schizophrenic psychosis, most of the time those affected can no longer distinguish between the outside world and the inside, and fall into a state of overexcitement that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of greatness, relationship disorders, or persecution mania.
Especially widespread is the hearing of voices: voices that give commands, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also common.
The affected person is no longer able to distinguish what is important from what is not, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like sleep, psychosis opens the door to a torrent of ideas and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is centered on the subject, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician at the general psychiatry clinic at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of events, everything has a meaning directed at him.
At the same time, he enters a passive role, as in a dream, feels overwhelmed by events and cannot actively organize them.
This is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
In general it is not possible to adjust reality to them, hallucinations are a cruel reality, awakening, impossible.
Having experienced a hallucination once in your life
In contrast to a dream, Fuchs says, “the spatial and sensory structure of reality that is perceived in psychosis remains in principle as it is.”
Paranoid thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the distancing of experience takes place in reality.
For the researchers, it is still unknown why our brains make convertibles.
According to Fuchs, states of emergency can lead anyone to temporarily lose contact with reality.
But not all people develop psychosis.
There appears to be a genetic disposition for schizophrenia, but studies in twins have shown that in addition to genes, there are other determinants.
The researchers assume that those affected suffer minimal brain damage.
We suspect that the brain’s neuronal maturity is affected at an early stage of development, such as through a mother’s viral disease during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
But it remains an unknown how this alteration of the neural system occurs, which also does not manifest itself at all for many years.
Also the influence of the environment plays an important role – stress or a traumatic experience can be the triggers of a psychosis when a predisposition already exists.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can cause psychosis, as they interfere with the brain’s transmission system.
When the brain warms up
The illogical thing about all this is that psychotic people suffer from hallucinations and take very expensive drugs to get rid of them, while others pay for drugs that allow them to experience some, says professor of psychology Erich Kasten of Lübeck.
Perceiving a hallucination as pleasant or not often depends on the point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and visions for ten years and has analyzed the results in the book Die unreale Welt in unserem Kopf (The unreal world in our head), published last year.
Hallucinations are among the typical accompanying symptoms of psychosis, but also, surprisingly, of many other diseases.
Among them are, along with mental disorders such as borderline personality disorder or depressions, often also diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer’s and cranial trauma.
Surprisingly and under certain conditions, the brains of healthy people also suffer hallucinations.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, are made up of memories that are normally suppressed.
They arise when the areas of the brain in which sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or poorly inhibited; when our brain gets warm, but also when stimuli are lacking.
Drugs can cause this condition in the same way as brain damage or psychosis.
But also the restriction of stimuli, stress, bad love or other exceptional brain states.
In recent studies, up to one-third of respondents reported having experienced a hallucination at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. was 16 years old, living in a small town in Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania and attending a secondary school.
A regular girl.
If it weren't for those images and voices.
Sometimes, during recreation, it happens that a clumsy boy with long, dark hair speaks to him.
When she answers, the other students look at her surprised; no one but her hears or sees the boy.
They think the shy girl is a somewhat strange dreamer, but Sarah K. knows she’s not dreaming.
She is awake and sees and hears that boy, just as she sees and hears the girl sitting on the bench next door.
You can even feel your presence, at least for a few moments.
It's a nice feeling, she likes the boy.
Sometimes she wonders if she’s crazy.
He also knows that the boy and the rest of the visions are not real and disappear.
At night, the apparitions are alarming.
Visions are often a burden.
When he is in class he can sometimes not follow the lesson because the teacher – in his eyes and ears – is presenting a new companion, while for the rest he explains in a visible and audible way the mathematical equations.
At night, the apparitions are alarming.
While waiting in the dark room for sleep to arrive, which often comes late and is scarce, she does not know whether she is awake or dreaming, whether the images she sees, the beaks or the girl with bleeding cuts in her arms and legs, appear in front of her eyes open or closed.
Leave me alone, yell at the figures.
Her parents and friends haven't told her anything, they'd think she's crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. Today is20 years old.
He approved selectivity last year and lives with his boyfriend.
A year ago, hallucinations disappeared.
Ever since she's been in contact with psychologist Kasten over the Internet, she knows she's not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art out of desperation.
According to Kasten, when a person is socially isolated or suffers from a stimulus restriction, it is very likely that after a while they will begin to have hallucinations.
I think the brain is unoccupied and is in charge of looking for entertainment.
Sarah K., only daughter, was a little afraid of the other children and often played alone.
Her hallucinations began when, at the age of 13, she learned that the man she’s called dad since she’s been using reason is not her biological father.
Since visual and acoustic hallucinations are active in the same areas of the brain that also process real impressions and noises, those affected like Sarah K. find it difficult to distinguish between visions and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "is in the brain, reality is projected there.
Hallucinations are also images that the brain produces, which is why they seem so real.”
Kasten also classifies nocturnal fantasies as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people do not differ fundamentally from those of an acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their visions as unreal.
Kasten therefore recommends his patients to appreciate their hallucinations as a special skill.
Limit situation between sleep and hallucination
In this world too focused on the conscious, imaginary experiences usually become pathological, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician at the psychiatry and psychotherapy clinic at the Florence-Nightingale-Krankenhauses hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a hard and painful disease but it also entails something positive and creative – madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has investigated so-called Oneirism, a special form of consciousness, which is perceived as a dream.
Dream hallucinations are almost very complex and detailed dreams that the person who experiences them considers real and that subsequently cannot differentiate from being awake.
Dream-conscious states arise in extreme situations associated with a trauma or a disease, such as in patients with polyradiculoneuropathy, who experience motor paralysis while fully conscious.
According to Schmidt-Degenhardt, when a person is threatened by a loss of self or the world due to a total and permanent motor disability, it replaces a very dangerous real situation with an imaginary world of its own that is decoupled from reality.
A form of boundary situation between sleep and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome a situation in reality, a world change occurs, although the real situation remains present in the imagination.
An intensive way of giving meaning and interpretation to an incomprehensible situation in itself that our own ability to create allows us not to sink into the nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
Also art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen of Zurich describes his dream experiences in his book Herzenwechsel as a soul-saving action.
He was 49 years old, when his conscience embarked on several-day trips following a heart valve surgery with heart transplant included, while his body was doomed to immobility at the intensive care station.
Claussen plunged into a world created by him and visited strange places of other times: he found himself prostrated in bed, an older man aboard a sanatorium on a train, a robot guarding his health.
It was seen in the High Middle Ages, surrounded by nobles who produced narcotics from blood.
A Greek on a motorcycle kidnapped him in his home country, surfed on his hospital bed in the Alps with snow firn and met a Korean mobster.
It gives everything in these imaginary facts, everything is real, even later in the memories.
For Claussen, these interior trips are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dreaming is a different state, so it describes your experience.
On the contrary, the memories of mental journeys are, many years later, much clearer, even in irrelevant details.
It’s clearer and more intense even than real experiences.
The intensity of this experience dilutes the horizon of the rest of our daily experiences, adds psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Finally, oneirism, psychosis, hallucinations and drug use show how fragile the inner reproduction of outer reality is, even when we are awake.
Every modification of the state of consciousness, summarizes psychologist Kasten, “can lead to a deformation of what we call reality.”
An experience that, on the other hand, can be completely enriching.
