75% of working mothers have had labor problems because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study 'Fecundidad y trajectoria laboral de las femmes en Espa<0xC3><0xB1>a', prepared by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75% of working mothers have seen limited opportunities in the workplace due to maternity.
The study points out that there are many differences in the start of coexistence as a couple and the number of children, depending on whether or not they work and the type of work they perform.
Those who do not have an activity outside the home, work part-time, or have an unstable job, start living together as a couple, advance the first maternity, and have more children.
In contrast, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, lag behind coexistence and motherhood, and have fewer offspring.
“Women aged 35-49 with fixed employment have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after commencing coexistence, a figure that increases to 4.1 women with fixed employment have needed longer of their life path to achieve them, which has led them to postpone the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of work performed exerts a lot of influence on maternity, albeit less on the timing of mating," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that differentiates the age of women in getting married and having the first offspring.
According to the survey, the higher the educational level, the greater the age at which they marry and at which they have their first child.
There is also a difference between women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35- to 49-year-old group, those with elementary and higher education were first-time mothers at an average of 25.1 and 32.1, respectively.
"Another division is also established among women according to their level of education.
While those with elementary education get married and have their first child before getting a stable job, those with middle or higher levels reverse this sequence and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child," Delgado says.
