Manuel Vicent presents in 'Poker of Ases' (Alfaguara, illustrations by Fernando Vicente) some thirty radiographs of writers who have gone through their literary life (and, in cases, also through the other).
It does not do so in the foreseeable and fearful genres (biographical resemblance, life and work), but seeks something similar to the ignition core of the creator character.
The journey has its excitements and Vicent spares no scares or illuminations.
In addition to an exquisite pleasure, the book is a moving invitation to reading and re-reading.
Here are some snapshots.
On Albert Camus: "In his pages I discovered that the Mediterranean was not a sea, but a spiritual, almost physical impulse, the same that I felt without giving it a name: pleasure against the unfortunate destiny, morality without guilt and innocence without any god."
About Samuel Beckett: "Nihilist, allegorical Christian, he wrote what he had in his blood, not in his intellect, between powerlessness and ignorance, with a dazzling poetic humor, meaningless, like the blade of a knife that was about to kill him."
About Graham Greene: "Our man was abducted by this woman with a passion that lasted thirteen years, in whose flesh he combined the emotion of adultery with the pleasure of remorse, a spiritual privilege that consisted in reaching heaven through the path of perdition."
About James Joyce: "The 'Ulises' was published in Paris in 1922 by Sylvia Beach. It is one of the eight thousand-meter peaks of universal literature, which must be climbed by the north wall, from which the best climbers emerge again and again."
About William Faulkner: "He was a weird guy.
Of himself, he sometimes said that he was the heir of a county landowner and others that he was the son of a black woman and a crocodile.
Both dreams were of greatness."
