The Cowardly Aggression
Last week, my mother of about 70 years old was walking through our neighborhood in the municipality of Fuenlabrada when a group of young people between 15 and 18 years of age passed by her and our dog, a specimen of mixed breed, rescued from the kennel and with no more than six kilograms of weight and, without intermediation, they kicked the dog two times.
Our indignation is capitalized because we do not find the fun in a free aggression to a small and helpless animal, which by the way, was tied.
To this must be added the suffocation that provoked a lady who walked quietly and who, when he rebuked these individuals, came to fear for their physical integrity, since an energist who attacks an animal, is able to do the same with a woman, a child, an old man or, in short, with anyone who is weaker than himself.
The incident occurred at five o'clock in the afternoon on any Tuesday for a traditionally quiet neighborhood.
The dog was crying all day.
By the way, we put a complaint in a nearby police station that we doubt it will serve for a long time and not to generate susceptibilities, only to clarify that the cowardly killers were Spanish.
Indignation has led us to denounce this fact.
We do not understand what is happening among young people so that they consider it fun to mistreat a helpless animal that gives us love, companionship and friendship for free.
We do not know where good education and respect for animals and people have gone.
Michelin and Fesvial together for helmet use
The tire manufacturer Michelin, with the collaboration of the Spanish Foundation for Road Safety (Fesvial), has launched a campaign to encourage the use of the helmet, mainly among younger drivers, both entities reported today.
This initiative seeks to raise awareness about the importance of using the helmet, as it is the only protective element capable of preventing head injuries or even death in the event of an accident while riding a motorcycle.
Michelin said this campaign is part of its commitment to road safety, which "goes beyond designing and manufacturing products that are safer every day," and said it also contributes to this goal through other pedagogical and informational actions.
This new campaign to promote helmet use on the motorcycle, under the motto 'To be or not to be', will have a first phase in which posters will be distributed in more than 500 motorcycle workshops, with the aim of achieving maximum dissemination.
To conclude, Michelin stressed that road safety "is a constant concern" for the company, since being a manufacturer of two-wheeled vehicles tires, one of its main goals is to develop increasingly safe products.
