Emergency braking assistance is now mandatory
As with ABS anti-lock brakes and will pass with ESP stability control, emergency braking assistance systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they are already in all cars and light commercial vehicles of new registration, while for the rest a period of absence is set until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase the protection of pedestrians although, because of its way of working, it can also help to avoid many collisions by scope.
The emergency braking assistant that does is increase the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects by the piston that the driver gives.
But he doesn’t always keep that pressure until the end.
According to a study carried out by the manufacturer of car components Bosch, a third of the drivers involved in an accident had not stepped on the brake before the collision and half of them did not take full advantage of the force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, requires the maximum to the braking system, reducing the distance that the car uses to stop.
According to a study by the EU itself, if all cars were equipped with such elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided per year.
The reduction will be even greater - it is estimated that one in four accidents with damage to people would be avoided - when so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (via a radar or camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and although collision is inevitable, the device exerts maximum effort on the brakes to minimize damage.
