How much should you charge for your Facebook profile?
Facebook users can know the salary they deserve according to their profile, thanks to a new application of Trovit, the search engine with the largest number of classified ads of real estate, employment and engine in Spain.
The tool How much should you charge? calculates the salaries of users from the more than 140,000 job offers that Trovit has in Spain, from a form available on Facebook, where they must enter their profession, years of experience, age and city where they want to work.
In the week that the application is running, the search engine has detected that in general the Spanish worker "feels poorly paid," Trovit's product manager, Albert Ribera, said in a statement.
According to data Trovit has from its search engines in the UK and France, Spaniards are the worst paid.
A British computer programmer charges 45,226 euros gross per year and a French programmer 31,059 euros gross per year, compared to 24,000 euros received by a Spanish programmer.
Similarly, a driver charges 34,247 euros net annually in England, 25,751 in France and 16,420 in Spain.
According to Trovit, the lowest paid job in Spain is that of a waiter, with 11,592 euros net annually; followed by that of a dependent, with 14,725 euros; and that of an operator, with 15,667 euros.
The most searched jobs on the web in the last three months are for the driver, the middle-day jobs and the social worker.
